ture of agribusiness and instituted key reforms in American farm labor. The authors also address the processes of social change involved in FLOC actions. Their findings are based on extensive research among farmworkers, growers, and representatives of agribusiness, as well as personal involvement with FLOC leaders and supporters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aMexican American migrant agricultural laborerszMiddle West. 0aMigrant agricultural laborerszMiddle West. 0aMigrant agricultural laborers--Middle West. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aReza, Ernesto M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aVelásquez, Baldemar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVelásquez, Baldemar.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70796240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292758919423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292758919/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK